[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":852},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F09\u002Freact-day-25-react-router-nested-routes\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F09\u002Freact-day-25-react-router-nested-routes\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F09\u002Freact-day-25-react-router-nested-routes\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F09\u002Freact-day-25-react-router-nested-routes\u002F":829,"related:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F09\u002Freact-day-25-react-router-nested-routes\u002F":838},"\u002Freact\u002F20221009\u002F2778078774\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":808,"date":809,"description":810,"extension":811,"lang":812,"meta":813,"navigation":108,"path":814,"readingMinutes":815,"seo":816,"standalone":817,"stem":818,"tags":819,"tldr":826,"updated":809,"url":827,"__hash__":828},"content\u002Fen\u002FReact\u002Freact-day-25-react-router-nested-routes.md","React, Why Not Learn It Now? - React Router - Nested Routes - (25)","1003017142",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":802},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,36,46,56,235,245,251,261,267,285,292,327,331,349,367,373,408,430,439,481,484,569,583,698,712,745,751,756,770,780,784,787,798],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"We've already covered the basics of React Router, so now it's time for another concept: nested routes. Nested routes show up all the time in real-world development, so in this post we're going to get familiar with them.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"switching-pages","Switching pages",[17,25,26,27,31,32,35],{},"Before we get into nested routes, there's one more piece of React Router we should meet first: ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"Link",". At the end of the last exercise, we switched routes in a pretty dumb way — we just typed ",[28,33,34],{},"\u002Ftodolist"," straight into the browser's address bar to get to the ToDoList page. Honestly, that's a silly way to do it. You're not going to make your users switch routes like that, right? So... how should we actually do it?",[17,37,38,39,41,42,45],{},"The proper way is to use React Router's ",[28,40,30],{}," to navigate to the page we want. So let's open up main.jsx and add a ",[28,43,44],{},"List"," here for now.",[17,47,48,49,51,52,55],{},"It's simple to use — just drop ",[28,50,44],{}," outside of ",[28,53,54],{},"Routes",". Here I also put together a quick little navbar.",[57,58,63],"pre",{"className":59,"code":60,"language":61,"meta":62,"style":62},"language-jsx shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","import React from 'react'\nimport { HashRouter, Route, Routes, Link } from \"react-router-dom\";\nimport ReactDOM from 'react-dom\u002Fclient'\nimport App from '.\u002FApp'\nimport '.\u002Findex.css'\nimport ToDoList from \".\u002FTodoList\";\n\nReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root')).render(\n  \u003CReact.StrictMode>\n    \u003CHashRouter>\n      \u003Cnav className=\"px-5 flex items-center h-[60px] bg-indigo-500 text-white\">\n        \u003Ch1 className=\"mr-auto text-2xl\">React TodoList\u003C\u002Fh1>\n        \u003Cul className=\"flex\">\n          \u003Cli className=\"mr-3\">\n            \u003CLink to=\"\u002F\" className=\"border p-3 hover:bg-indigo-600 duration-500\">Home\u003C\u002FLink>\n          \u003C\u002Fli>\n          \u003Cli>\n            \u003CLink to=\"\u002Ftodolist\" className=\"border p-3 hover:bg-indigo-600 duration-500\">ToDoList\u003C\u002FLink>\n          \u003C\u002Fli>\n        \u003C\u002Ful>\n      \u003C\u002Fnav>\n      \u003CRoutes>\n        \u003CRoute path=\"\u002F\" element={ \u003CApp \u002F> } \u002F>\n        \u003CRoute path=\"\u002Ftodolist\" element={ \u003CToDoList \u002F> } \u002F>\n      \u003C\u002FRoutes>\n    \u003C\u002FHashRouter>\n  \u003C\u002FReact.StrictMode>\n)\n","jsx","",[28,64,65,73,79,85,91,97,103,110,116,122,128,134,140,146,152,158,164,170,176,181,187,193,199,205,211,217,223,229],{"__ignoreMap":